particular, the arbitrage community - who felt that its demands were
'onerous'. There was no immediate response from AT&amp;T.
AT&amp;T commenced the bidding for NCR five months ago with a Dollars 90-a-share
cash offer, while NCR said that it was looking for Dollars 125 a share.
However, NCR subsequently dropped this request to Dollars 110 a share, and
at the weekend AT&amp;T said it would meet this figure, but switched from cash
terms to a paper consideration.
Mr Exley then said that he was concerned about a fall in the AT&amp;T share
price between now and the stage at which the offer closed.
