third court appearance on theft and false-accounting charges totalling
Pounds 25m, Raymond Hughes writes.
Sir David Hopkin, the chief metropolitan magistrate, agreed that in future
Mr Nadir (pictured) need report to his local police station only once a week
 -between 7pm and 9pm on Mondays - instead of daily. The requirement was one
of the conditions on which Mr Nadir was granted Pounds 3.5m bail in
December. Another was that he must live and sleep at his Mayfair home. That
was varied yesterday to enable him to travel out of London overnight.
Mr Simon Browne-Wilkinson, for the Serious Fraud Office, asked for the case
to be adjourned until July 23. He said the case should be ready for transfer
to a crown court within six months.
Sir David decided that the next hearing would be on July 9 when, he said, Mr
Nadir need not attend court.
