FT  24 APR 91 / Brazil takes assets freeze to court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Brazilian government will appeal to the Supreme Court this week to stop
a wave of judgments allowing people to withdraw cruzados blocked in an
Dollars 80bn (Pounds 47.3bn) asset freeze last year, alleging that the
resulting increase in money supply could scupper its economic stabilisation
plan, Christina Lamb writes from Rio.
Ms Zelia Cardoso, the economy minister, said on Brazilian television: 'If
the court decides that all the money should be liberated I wash my hands of
all responsibility over what may happen to inflation.'
The government appeal comes in response to a series of regional court
decisions declaring its asset freeze, the centrepiece of a drastic
anti-inflation plan, unconstitutional. This has led people to ask the courts
to free their money. There are 70,000 cases pending.
